<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910318-0141</DOCNO><DOCID>910318-0141.</DOCID><HL>   First Capital Boosts Its Loss Reserves,   Weighs Asset Sale; Chairman Resigns   ----   By Rhonda L. Rundle   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>03/18/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6</SO><CO>   FCH WNEWS</CO><IN>TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)INSURANCE (INS)LIFE INSURANCE (INL)EARNINGS (ERN)BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)</IN><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- First Capital Holdings Corp., stung bydefaults in its junk bond portfolio, bolstered its lossreserves by $34.8 million and announced the resignation ofits 49-year-old founder and chairman, Robert I. Weingarten.   The insurance holding company also said it is in &quot;seriousdiscussions&quot; to sell for about $150 million all of theuniversal life insurance business of the parent's FirstCapital Life Insurance Co. subsidiary in order to increasecapital.</LP><TEXT>   First Capital said that &quot;defaults and announced intentionsto default by some (bond) issuers&quot; forced it to increasereserves and adjust fourth-quarter results, which were firstreported on Feb. 12. Those results were depressed by $45.3million of investment reserve additions.   The adjusted fourth-quarter figure is a net loss of $24.7million, or 53 cents a fully diluted share. First Capitalinitially reported net income of $10.2 million, or 22 cents afully diluted share. In the year-earlier quarter, the companyposted net income of $17.4 million, or 37 cents a share.   Adjusted full-year net income is $7.1 million, or 15 centsa share, down sharply from the $41.9 million, or 90 cents ashare, reported initially. In 1989, the company had netincome of $69.5 million, or $1.49 a share.   First Capital said that according to accounting rules itsresults technically were adjusted rather than restatedbecause the changes were made prior to the filing offinancial statements with the Securities and ExchangeCommission.   First Capital declined to give any details about itsproposed sale of the universal life business, representingabout $1.3 billion in assets, or 30% of the First CapitalLife Insurance subsidiary. The subsidiary, formerly E.F.Hutton Life before it was acquired by First Capital,pioneered the universal life product.   Mr. Weingarten, who founded the company in 1983, resignedFriday as chairman, chief executive officer and a director,with 7 1/2 years left on his long-term employment agreement.Under the agreement, in which he becomes a companyconsultant, his annual salary will be cut to $500,000 from $1million.   Despite the timing of the resignation, First Capital andMr. Weingarten maintained that it wasn't related to thecompany's souring investments in high-yield, high-risk bonds.About 23.5% of First Capital's $8 billion in assets isinvested in below-investment grade securities.   In an interview, Mr. Weingarten stoutly denied that he hadbeen pushed out. &quot;I wasn't asked to leave. I've been sayingfor a couple of years that I might go, but it was never theright time.&quot;   Mr. Weingarten said he paved the way in 1988 when he soldthe bulk of his First Capital stock for $40 million to a unitof American Express Co. His wife, Palomba Weingarten,exercised an option the following year to buy Pilgrim GroupInc., a mutual fund concern, from First Capital for $11.5million.   Gerry R. Ginsberg, 50, will take over the helm, althoughin title he remains president and chief operating officer.The chief executive post wasn't filled. Another board member,Richard K. DeScherer, 46, was elected acting chairman. PhilipA. Fitzpatrick, executive vice president and chief financialofficer, was named a director, filling the seat vacated byMr. Weingarten.   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading Friday, FirstCapital shares closed at $3.125, unchanged. The news wasreleased after the close of trading.</TEXT></DOC>